04583nam a22007335i 9780231518499DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979739370  a97802315184997 a10.7312/groy146182doi  a(DE-B1597)456953  a(OCoLC)794494051  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aN7445.4b.G7613 2015 7aPHI0180002bisacsh04a302.23012231 aGroys, Boris, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnder Suspicion :bA Phenomenology of Media /cBoris Groys. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Themes in Philosophy, Social Criticism, and the Arts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTranslator ’s Preface: Dead Man Thinking -- tIntroduction -- tI. Submedial Space -- t1. The Submedial Subject and the Flux of Signs -- t2. The Truth of the Medial and the State of Exception -- t3. Media-Ontological Suspicion and Philosophical Doubt -- t4. The Phenomenology of Medial Sincerity -- t5. The Gaze of the Other -- t6. The Medium Becomes the Message -- t7. The Case of Exception and the Truth of the Medial -- tII. The Economy of Suspicion -- t8. Marcel Mauss: Symbolic Exchange; or, Civilization Under Water -- t9. Claude Lévi-Strauss: Mana ; or, the Floating Signifi er -- t10. Georges Bataille: The Potlatch with the Sun -- t11. Jacques Derrida: The Lack of Time and Its Specters -- t12. Jean-François Lyotard: The Roller Coaster of the Sublime -- t13. The Time of Signs -- t14. Suspicion Is the Medium -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe public generally regards the media with suspicion and distrust. Therefore, the media's primary concern is to regain that trust through the production of sincerity. Advancing the field of media studies in a truly innovative way, Boris Groys focuses on the media's affect of sincerity and its manufacture of trust to appease skeptics.Groys identifies forms of media sincerity and its effect on politics, culture, society, and conceptions of the self. He relies on different philosophical writings thematizing the gaze of the other, from the theories of Heidegger, Sartre, Mauss, and Bataille to the poststructuralist formulations of Lacan and Derrida. He also considers media "states of exception" and their creation of effects of sincerity—a strategy that feeds the media's predilection for the extraordinary and the sensational, further fueling the public's suspicions. Emphasizing the media's production of emotion over the presentation (or lack thereof) of "facts," Groys launches a timely study boldly challenging the presumed authenticity of the media's worldview.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAesthetics, Modern -- 20th century. 0aAesthetics, Moderny20th century. 0aArt -- Philosophy. 0aArtxPhilosophy. 0aPostmodernism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh1 aStrathausen, Carsten.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/groy1461840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231518499423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231518499/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK